  "summary": "After searching a study and ensuring all drawers were locked to avoid detection by the meticulous Rupert Bettman, Jimmy leaves the room. In the hallway, he encounters Bettman, who claims he was investigating a potential thief. Jimmy notices a bulge in Bettman's pocket, suggesting he is carrying a gun, and mockingly refers to him as an \"ape.\" Jimmy claims he is looking for cookies because a tin labeled for guests was empty. He later reveals he has hidden a heap of cookies in a dressing table drawer, intending to eat them despite finding them unappetizing. He notes that Bettman is suspicious, carries a gun, and seems to never sleep.\n\nLater, Bondell and Loran arrive at the house after their car, a Sienna, breaks down. They are greeted by Mrs. Cutter and join O'Roke and others for lunch. Loran engages Bettman in conversation, praising his vast knowledge. A game of clockwork golf follows, featuring Bettman, Loran, O'Roke, and Bondell; Bettman and Loran emerge victorious. Jimmy joins the group, appearing confident. After lunch, Jimmy offers to drive the girls to the garage, complaining of indigestion caused by eating too many cookies. Bondell and Loran discuss their successful attempt to trick Bettman and O'Rourke. Jimmy remarks that while O'Rourke was easy to handle, Bettman is \"omnipresent,\" appearing silently and everywhere.",
